      Who controls Ben & Jerry=E2=80=99s?
   =20
 =20
One very natural thing that can happen is:=09You start a company. You are a=
 passionate and visionary founder; the company is built in your image, and =
its success comes from following your philosophy. Perhaps it is even named =
after you.=09It becomes very valuable.=09You would like to sell your stock =
in the company for a ton of money, because money can be used for many thing=
s that you like (philanthropy, yachts, etc.).=09But you would like to conti=
nue to control the company, because you care passionately about it but also=
 because its value is dependent on your unique vision and you don=E2=80=99t=
 want someone else to mess that up.Traditionally, ownership and control rig=
hts are connected: If you own 51% of the stock of the company, you can repl=
ace the board of directors and appoint the chief executive officer and gene=
rally tell the company what to do; if you sell that 51% to someone else the=
n they get to do those things. But modern corporate finance is pretty flexi=
ble and there are ways around that. In particular, if you are a visionary f=
ounder and you want to take your company public, you can do it with dual-cl=
ass stock, so you can sell a bunch of your stock and still keep control of =
the company. Snap Inc. even went public with=C2=A0  non-voting=C2=A0stock: =
The founders could get lots of cash for their company without giving up any=
 control at all.In theory you could do even weirder things. You could sell =
100% of the stock of the company to a single buyer, in a merger,=C2=A0and k=
eep control anyway. Just write in the merger agreement =E2=80=9CBuyer will =
own Company, but Seller will get to appoint its board of directors, who wil=
l continue to run the company.=E2=80=9D A very weird thing to do! And no re=
ason to think a buyer would agree. But I guess it=E2=80=99s theoretically p=
ossible, why not. Or you could slice it more finely: =E2=80=9CBuyer will ow=
n Company and run it, but Seller will continue to appoint an=C2=A0independe=
nt board of directors, who will have final say over philosophical matters.=
=E2=80=9D That way you get your money, and someone else takes over the prob=
lems of running the business day to day, but the company still has to follo=
w your broad vision. It=E2=80=99s still your passion project, so the elemen=
ts that you are passionate about preserving =E2=80=94=C2=A0the parts of you=
r vision that made it so valuable =E2=80=94=C2=A0are still in your control.=
This doesn=E2=80=99t happen a lot or anything, but  it did happen with Ben =
& Jerry=E2=80=99s:Ben & Jerry=E2=80=99s sued its corporate parent, Unilever=
 Plc, to block a deal that would allow its ice cream to be sold in the Isra=
eli-occupied West Bank, claiming that would conflict with the company=E2=80=
=99s =E2=80=9Ccore values.=E2=80=9DThe ice cream maker said Unilever=E2=80=
=99s decision to sell the Ben & Jerry=E2=80=99s brand and trademark rights =
in Israel to businessman Avi Zinger violates its 2000 acquisition agreement=
 with the global food, home care and beauty products giant.=E2=80=9CBen & J=
erry=E2=80=99s founders insisted on the inclusion of explicit language to e=
nsure the brand=E2=80=99s integrity was not diluted,=E2=80=9D following the=
 sale to Unilever, setting up an independent board with authority to protec=
t its brand, reputation and goodwill, the company said in the lawsuit, file=
d Tuesday in Manhattan federal court.=C2=A0Here is the complaint. In genera=
l it is very unusual for a subsidiary to sue its corporate parent, because =
the parent makes all decisions for the subsidiary and is not about to sue i=
tself. But Ben & Jerry=E2=80=99s Homemade Inc. has an independent board of =
directors, and only two of its members are appointed by Unilever. (They vot=
ed not to sue.) Here is the 2000=C2=A0merger agreement in which Unilever bo=
ught Ben & Jerry=E2=80=99s; Section 6.14 covers the independent board of di=
rectors, e.g.:The Company Board shall have primary responsibility for prese=
rving and enhancing the objectives=C2=A0of the historical social mission of=
 the Company as they may evolve from time to time consistent therewith (=E2=
=80=9CSocial Mission Priorities=E2=80=9D). The Company Board shall work tog=
ether with the CEO to integrate Social Mission Priorities into the business=
 of the Surviving Corporation. ...The Company Board shall be the custodians=
 of the Ben & Jerry=E2=80=99s-brand image and shall have primary responsibi=
lity for safeguarding the integrity of the essential elements of the Ben & =
Jerry=E2=80=99s brand-name (the =E2=80=9CEssential Integrity of the Brand=
=E2=80=9D). The Company Board shall work together with the CEO to provide t=
hat the business of the Surviving Corporation is conducted in a manner that=
 preserves and enhances the Essential Integrity of the Brand. As part of th=
is responsibility, the Company Board may prevent any action bythe CEO in th=
e areas of new product introduction, the changing of product standards and =
specifications, the approval of the content of marketing materials and the =
licensing or other use of the Ben & Jerry=E2=80=99s trademark that, in each=
 case, a majority of the Company Board reasonably determines to be inconsis=
tent with the Essential Integrity of the Brand.And the board gets to more o=
r less appoint itself: The majority of directors are =E2=80=9CClass I Direc=
tors,=E2=80=9D meaning the board as of the merger and their successors, and=
 when a Class I director leaves then the other Class I directors appoint a =
successor. Unilever=C2=A0owns=C2=A0Ben & Jerry=E2=80=99s, but Ben (Cohen) a=
nd Jerry (Greenfield) and their friends still=C2=A0control=C2=A0it, or part=
ly control it, or think they do anyway. They have sold the stock, but the v=
oting rights they keep forever.
