nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  <em>non-v=
oting=C2=A0</em>stock</a>: The founders could get lots of cash for their co=
mpany without giving up any control at all.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>In theory you could do even weirder things. You could sell 100% of the sto=
ck of the company to a single buyer, in a merger,=C2=A0and keep control any=
way. Just write in the merger agreement =E2=80=9CBuyer will own Company, bu=
t Seller will get to appoint its board of directors, who will continue to r=
un the company.=E2=80=9D A very weird thing to do! And no reason to think a=
 buyer would agree. But I guess it=E2=80=99s theoretically possible, why no=
